The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Tuesday, November 02, 2004 

 Crash injured brought to Delhi

 OUR BUREAU

 Nov. 1: The survivors of the Uttaranchal crash in which eight tourists from Bengal were killed were flown to Delhi from Joshimath tonight.

 Four of them have been admitted to AIIMS and 13 others to Safdarjung Hospital. 

 The injured include three children. A state government official from Delhi said relatives can call 09811666651 and 09811666653 for information.

 Earlier, the state government said it will bear the medical expenses of the survivors.

 Inspector-general, law and order, Chayan Mukherjee said at Writers? Buildings a team of officers has left for Chameli in the Himalayan state. ?The bodies are now in the custody of the Chameli superintendent of police. They will be cremated at Hrishikesh.? 

 The tourists were heading to Badrinath from Joshimath when their bus skidded off a cliff near Lambagarh in inclement weather.

 As a government representative, transport minister Subhas Chakraborty today came here, 15 km from the city, to see Samir Kumar Ghosh, who lost his wife and five relatives. 

 Ghosh?s wife Anjali, 37, his brothers-in-law ? Ujjal Das, 55, Asim Dey, 52, and Amiya Dey, 45 ? and sister-in-law Minati were among the dead. His daughter Moumita has suffered injury in the head. 

 The others killed were Piyush Saha of Konnagar and Mallika Das of Calcutta.

 The minister said he would leave for the capital tomorrow to organise treatment for the survivors.




